[2]
Date: Tue 19 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Nebraska Health and Human Services System, Tue 19 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://www.hhs.state.ne.us/new/1102nr/hepc.htm>

Number of Clinic-based Hepatitis C Cases in Fremont Announced
-------------------------------------------------------------
LINCLON: The Nebraska Health and Human Services System (HHSS) today
announced the number of people treated at a Fremont oncology clinic who
tested positive for hepatitis C. Of the 612 patients of Dr. Tahir Javed's
oncology clinic who received letters advising them to be tested, 485 chose
to be tested for the virus, and of these, 81 tested positive. The letters
were issued as part of an investigation which began when several cases of
hepatitis C were reported from the Fremont area. Health officials found the
most likely link to be care given at Dr. Javed's clinic, said Dr. Tom
Safranek, state epidemiologist with HHSS. The clinic is no longer in
operation. The letters were sent in mid-October to patients who were
treated at the clinic between 1 Mar 2000 and 31 Dec 2001. HHSS offered a
testing clinic in Fremont 17 October 2002 through 1 November 2002.
Hepatitis C is a viral infection of the liver and the most common
bloodborne infection in the country. The virus causes no symptoms in most
cases and the majority of carriers do not know they are infected. Infected
individuals may experience fatigue, loss of appetite and yellowing of the
skin. The virus affects the liver and can eventually lead to cirrhosis or
cancer of the liver.
Possible routes of transmission are being investigated, Safranek said. The
illness is spread through blood and bodily fluids. It can be transmitted
through intravenous lines or injections if proper infection control
practices are not followed. The virus is not transmitted by casual contact.
Hepatitis C can be treated with a drug called interferon, alone or in
combination with the drug ribavirin. Genotype 3A of hepatitis C, which is
what these patients have, shows a favorable response to treatment,
according to Safranek. Patients of the clinic who haven't yet been tested
should contact their physician or call the Health and Human Services System
at (402) 471-9252. Blood tests are needed to confirm the presence of the virus.
More information can be found on the HHS System's Web site at
or at
or
<http://www.consensus.nih.gov/cons/116/091202116cdc_statement.htm .>
